	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Negotiations continue but West Africa insists on conditions</h1>

			
			<h4>
												07 June 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> Soumaïla Cissé, President of the UEMOA Commission, and Victor Gbeho, President of the ECOWAS Commission, in a joint West Africa-EU ministerial meeting held in Mali on 6 May 2010 to review the progress in EPA negotiations, reiterated that without EU funding for an EPA development programme (PAPED), West Africa does not envisage signing the EPA. As a consequence, the West African states have requested the EU to provide ‘an appropriate response to West Africa’s financing plan for the PAPED during the next negotiations scheduled for Brussels between 11 and 12 May 2010’. This view was shared by the Malian and Nigerian ministers, who in their opening statements jointly called upon Ghana and Côte d’Ivoire, which have already signed interim EPAs, to join West Africa in concluding an inclusive and balanced regional EPA. West Africa, although willing to exercise some flexibility in areas such as rules of origin and market access, is insisting that EPAs must be supportive of regional development and must also act as a strong catalyst to the development of the industrial base of individual countries. The participants at the ministerial meeting underscored the need for an expeditious finalisation of the West Africa common external tariff (CET) concurrently with a new protocol on rules of origin, in order to consolidate regional integration and ensure that ultimately the region will not be short-changed in its access to the EU market under the EPA. On other related issues, West Africa has clearly expressed its dissatisfaction with the EU’s attempt to extend the existing non-execution clause (relating to member states’ compliance with democracy and good governance requirements) in the Cotonou Partnership Agreement into the EPA. They consider that this requirement would be not only alien to a trade agreement such as the EPA, but also inconsistent with WTO requirements. Moreover, the ministers insisted that ‘under no circumstance’ should political dialogue instruments contained in the Cotonou Agreement be used in trade relations between West Africa and the EU. Given the role played by the private sector in any export-led economy, West Africa is keen to get more private-sector involvement in the EPA negotiations, not least because this sector will bear the brunt of future changes in the tariff structure as a result of the adoption of a West Africa regional CET. Consequently, the involvement of the private sector will undoubtedly assist in securing their interests in a future EPA, and will be necessary to ensure acceptability of the final agreement. In order to facilitate a common position on the EPA, West Africa is currently finalising a CET in five major areas to be identified by both ECOWAS and UEMOA secretariats.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
