				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In terms of market access, West Africa has offered to liberalise 70% of its market over a twenty-five-year period, with a five-year moratorium. Because 12 of the 15 West African countries negotiating the EPA are least developed countries, West Africa hopes to protect the remaining 30% of the market to ensure that the customs revenues on which these LDCs depend is not disrupted. As regards some of the remaining issues in the negotiations, it is important also to note that the West African Ministerial Monitoring Committee (MMC) earlier recommended that the regional negotiators, along with their counterparts in the EU, seek possible solutions aimed at sustainable EU finances to regional integration initiatives. As regards the MFN clause, West Africa seems willing to accept it if considered only on a case-by-case basis. This arguably implies that the long-debated MFN multiplier clause will form part of an eventual West Africa-EU EPA on a sector-by-sector basis. However, it remains to be seen how the issues of MFN, agricultural subsidies and rules of origins will be handled in the forthcoming meetings of technical and senior officials planned for 7-11 June 2010 in Togo. </p>
		</div>
		
